So this is not a great way to scale up an Ethereum infrastructure project. So Rivet's solution, and this is part of our open source Ether Cattle Initiative, is we introduced replications. So the basic idea is that you have one master node that connects to peers and verifies data from the peers, and we can actually support more than one master. You need one for this to work, but you can have more than one for redundancy. So that, again, you don't have that single point of failure at your master. And then the data is streamed through a system called Kafka to servers that we call Replicas. Now, the Replicas, they're not verifying the information. The benefits of this are that Replicas don't have to do the verification overhead, so they can dedicate 100% of their resources to or 98% because they got to pull stuff from Kafka and write it to disk.
